sentence: Crude continues slide on weak U.S. employment data .
Investing.com - Crude oil futures extended losses on Friday as weaker-than-expected jobs numbers fueled sentiment the U.S. economy is cooling and will need less fuels to operate .

On the New York Mercantile Exchange , light , sweet crude futures for delivery in August traded at USD85 .01 a barrel on Friday , down 2.53 % , off from a session high of USD87 .09 and up from an earlier session low of USD84 .27 .
Earlier Friday , the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics reported the economy added a net 80,000 nonfarm payrolls in June , below market forecasts for a gain of around 90,000 .
April figures were revised to 68,000 from 77,000 nonfarm payrolls , while May 's numbers were revised to 77,000 from 69,000 .
The service sector in the U.S. also slipped in June , a separate report shows .
The Institute of Supply Management 's non-manufacturing purchasing managers ' index fell to 52.1 in June from 53.7 in May .
The news sent oil plummeting on sentiment that the world 's largest economy is growing increasingly stagnant and will demand less fuels and energy going forward .
Oil fell on global fears as well .
International Monetary Fund Managing Director Christine Lagarde , meanwhile , said the fund would likely cut its global growth forecasts , which also sent oil tanking .
The market shrugged off a European Central Bank decision to trim its benchmark interest rate 25 basis points to 0.75 % , focusing instead on the cooling nature of the European economy .

A Bank of England decision to inject GBP50 billion into the economy via stimulus measures followed by interest rate cuts in China sent investors selling oil and snapping up safe and liquid dollar positions .
On the ICE Futures Exchange , Brent oil futures for August delivery were down 2.14 % and trading at USD98 .55 a barrel , up USD13 .54 from its U.S. counterpart .
